fields.customfield_13936:
Workaround for EBS-M file production failure due to Corrupted/Mismatch versions of PM-MOM and counter-mapping files:

1) Delete the PM-MOM.x.xml file from:     /ericsson/pmic1/ebsm/data/eniqoutput/
2) Delete the counter-mapping.xml file from:     /ericsson/pmic1/ebsm/data/ebsm/countermapping/
3) Delete the older backups of PM-MOM files from:     /ericsson/pmic1/ebsm/backup/pmmos/

Workaround for high logging issue due to ROP expiry:
Steps to clear stale entries in ebsm database:
1) Login to master postgres pod
2) Login to ebsm db using below command from master postgres pod:
    /usr/bin/psql -Upostgres -d ebsm
3) Execute below command to clear the stale entries:
    delete from rop where rop_start_date_time like '20240724%' and processing_state_id=2;

*{color:#d04437}1. Detailed problem description:{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

The Network Viewer does not display nodes on the map even though the geographic coordinates associated with the node are part of the database. The nodes have been previously set to have a geographic position, and when adding the nodes to the ENM, they are successfully synchronized with the ENM.
{code:java}
FDN : "MeContext=ML66-10-41-99-206,ManagedElement=ML66-10-41-99-206,SystemFunctions=1,SysM=1,BasicNeData=1"
alarmFilterTime : 5
backupConfigChangedTimer : 900
basicNeDataId : "1"
configChangedFromLastBackup : CONFIGCHANGED
dcnHostMtuRouted : 0
dcnMode : VLAN
dcnVrfName : <empty>
elevation : "0.0"
enablePowerRedundancy : DISABLE
latitude : "47.33969"
legalNotice : <empty>
longitude : "18.8855"
neContact : "ejzslsz"
neDescription : "MINI-LINK 6600"
neLocation : "CAB49"
neName : "ML66-10-41-99-206"
neNotes : "You can add information in this Description field that will be included in the Node Report, for example additional notes for troubleshooting or archiving purposes. Max allowed numbers of characters in this Description field is 800."
neRestartReason : NPU_COLD_MGMT
neRestartScheduledCommands : WARMRESTART
neRestartScheduledEnable : DISABLE
neRestartScheduledTime : <empty>
pmStartTime : "00:00:00"
telecomStandard : ETSI{code}
However, when a node is placed on a map (Set Location), the set coordinate is written out to the node.

If the node placement is done with a node software version where the feature was not yet supported and the node is upgraded later, the data will not be written from ENM to the node.

*{color:#d04437}2. Expected behaviour or results:{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

The following operation would be desirable:
 # if the geographic position in the node is different from the default (Lat 0, Long 0, Elev 0), then the data read out from the node should be used in the Network Viewer
 # if the ENM has a geographic position stored and the node does not (e.g. for the reason above), then the data stored in the ENM should be written out to the node
 # if there is a discrepancy between the two data:

 * the user has modified the coordinates in the ENM and the node is unreachable, the ENM shall update the coordinates when the node becomes available again (assuming that the configuration file sequence number on the node remains the same as when the node was last synchronized with the ENM).
 * the user has modified the coordinates in the Node GUI. In this case, the sequence number of the configuration file has been increased and ENM will perform a full CM synchronization and shall update the coordinates from the node.

We have looked at the Jira ticket [https://eteamproject.internal.ericsson.com/browse/TORF-501211] and believe that storing two different sets of values for the same purpose is not the best solution.

Always.

fields.description:
MINI-LINK Indoor installation in NCM is failing when the node is having hRLB config. This issue can be seen in releases when a schema update related to support of sub-ports for Router6678 (neType: R6000-2) was delivered to allow ports also constraint based on sub-port ID along with other existing constraints. This delivery was for Router6000 node family and must not have impacted any MINI-LINK use cases.

The hRLB WAN port and member RLT port are normally reported with same Rack-Slot-Port and port type (TRANSPORT) details. They differ from bearer signal type perspective (ETH_BONDING and RL-IME correspondingly) and port interface type perspective (11 and 7 correspondingly).

The latest composite key is failing to confirm uniqueness as it is not considering the port interface type (preferably) anymore. During the flushing/saving the sync details, NCM is facing this objection from database and not able to declare the node as installed. As a result, those nodes are not seen in NCM UI also for further management.

Details can be found in this Jira : [https://eteamproject.internal.ericsson.com/browse/TORF-726600]

fields.customfield_37311:
This issue was introduced by MR 001541 FDN solution for EBS-N CUUP Link counters support with G4 (G4-SP084).

The issue is applicable to G2, G3 and G4.

MR 001541 changed EBS-N handling of CUUP Link counters from being CM based to a Fake FDN solution. The change means EBS-N no longer needs to consume CM Notifications on queue, EbsDeltaNotificationEventChannel, for the following CUUP Link MO types:

EP_NgU
S1ULink
RpUserPlaneLink
PpControlLink
The issue is that the CM Notifications are still placed on the EbsDeltaNotificationEventChannel even though EBS is no longer consuming them, resulting in the queue being constantly full. The solution is to no longer place CM notifications for the MO types above on the queue.

The issue was introduced in 24.05. It needs to be delivered to 24.08, and dropped back to 24.07 and 24.06 (and potentially 24.05 depending on CD customer plans, TMO & Swisscom).

Filter models was not removed from ebs-topology-service-models.

*{color:#d04437}1. Detailed problem description:{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

secserv has been observed to be sending very large (~70KB+) messages towards Log transformer (LT). Due to the large size of these logs, they are trimmed and end up as malformed JSON strings (i.e. without a matching closing bracket), which cannot be parsed by Log Transformer. As a result, these logs are not parsed by LT and never end up stored in Elasticsearch. Additionally, LT writes these messages to its own container logs, and it is the combination of the size & rate of these that is causing issues with LT in addition to incurring a higher performance cost.

I have attached an example LT log that includes the original secserv log.

These logs appear to be a long list of configuration parameters in XML format - the value of which should be clarified ideally as they come with a higher processing cost than most other logs. If there is a requirement for these logs to be kept in, perhaps they should be split up into chunks and sent in batches in order to avoid the issue entirely and ensure they are correctly handled by LT and stored by Elasticsearch.

*{color:#d04437}2. Expected behaviour or results:{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

In general, the expectation is for applications to avoid sending very large logs (e.g. stack traces/user or node lists) to Log Transformer in order for them to be processed adequately. The [+Java coding guidelines+|https://confluence-oss.seli.wh.rnd.internal.ericsson.com/display/Classic/Java+Coding+Guidelines] for example specify that collections should not be printed directly (Logging guidelines #11), which appears to be the case in this situation.

The value these logs bring is usually not well stated (e.g. stack traces) either, so it would be beneficial if they were removed/kept to a minimum. Crucially, since these very large secserv logs never make it to Elasticsearch, if they are absolutely required changes should be made to their size to ensure they can be processed by LT. Otherwise, they should be removed if they provide no meaningful value to users/customers.

*{color:#d04437}3. Activity and/or conditions during which this bug was found:{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

This issue has been observed on all cENM XL servers with load.

*{color:#d04437}4. Tester impact :{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

Included above.

*{color:#d04437}5. Potential Customer and/or System impact :{color}* 
----------------------------------------------------------

As a result of these logs being malformed JSON, they are not processed by Log Transformer and will not end up being stored in Elasticsearch. Therefore, a customer would be missing whatever information they would bring.

Lastly, there is a higher cost associated with parsing these types of very large logs in LT, so removing/reducing these would net performance gains in Log Transformer as well.

*{color:#d04437}6. Frequency of Fault{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

This issue is always seen on loaded cENM XL servers.

*{color:#d04437}7. Troubleshooting completed:{color}*
----------------------------------------------------------

We have done an analysis into the different SGs that are seen to be sending very large malformed JSON logs towards Log Transformer, and have identified secserv as one of the contributors to this issue, with these logs being generated daily on most XL cENM server.
